title.narrative: Property rights clear, secure, and reflected in accessible information base

baseline.value: 2.4 million property units in registry system and information from system accessible to public

target.value: Continued increase number of registered property units. Continued improvements in quality of registry operations, communications,and reputation.

actual.value: Continued increase in number of registered property units. Continued improvements in quality of registry operations,communications, and reputation.

title.narrative: 1c. Capacity developed in agency financial management and procurement

baseline.value: All financial management except for Project unit operate according to historic practices without exposure to internationalstandards. No agency-wide transparency of financial management data.

target.value: Further implementation of integrated accounting and reporting systems in local registration offices.

actual.value: Implementation of integrated accounting and reporting systems in local registration offices is ongoing.

comment.narrative: Internal audit unit established. Internal auditors selected and audit methodology developed.Achieved.

title.narrative: 1d. Land and real estate registry records are more secure and accessible

baseline.value: Archives well organized and maintained, but at risk of fire, weather, and other hazards. Few historical records digitized.Over-reliance on paper records which is inefficient.

target.value: Improved climate control for archives well-maintained and imaging of current records fully operational for all local land offices.

actual.value: Climate control for archives maintained. In all local offices sporadic imaging of current records implemented and it is operational.

title.narrative: 2b. Cadastral maps in selected areas upgraded and accessible

baseline.value: Digital cadastre map coverage incomplete yet required in some areas either because of active land markets or encroachment risks.

target.value: Cumulative digitized cadastral maps for 1.5 million land parcels, of which 680,000 geo-referenced by additional GPS field survey.Integration with other data.

actual.value: In total digitized cadastral maps for 1.88 million land parcels including geo-referencing of 722, 000 with additional field survey.

target.value: Project management ensures completion of project in accordance with revised schedule.

title.narrative: 3b Training for education and professional bodies

baseline.value: First project, SIDA support, and USAID Land Reform Project included some training for professionals.

title.narrative: 1e. Organizational structure and facilities are financially sustainable

baseline.value: Gosregister comprises 49 separate local self-financed registry offices plus a headquarters financed by the ongoing project andgovernment budget.

target.value: All operational expenses, including those of headquarters functions covered by income from registration.

actual.value: GIS Center has been established. All operational expenses, including those of headquarters functions covered by income fromregistration.

baseline.value: Gosregister staff well-trained but will continue to require more human resource development to address further development ofGos-register.

actual.value: 111 courses for DCR and LROs management and specialists, 3694 participants were trained.

title.narrative: 2c. Valuation information accessible and being used.

baseline.value: Government legislation regarding implementing regulations for property tax valuation is still pending in parliament. Price indexinformation not created.

target.value: Property sales price index (a module of the sales database) continues to be available to public for free on website.

actual.value: Immovable property price index is published on the website of the DCR for free.

title.narrative: 1b. IT system upgraded, with arrangements established for post-project operational sustainability.

baseline.value: IT Unit within PIU has supervised IT improvement and has been funded by donor projects.

actual.value: Integration of the central system has been completed.

title.narrative: Sustainable system for land and real estate registration and cadastre

baseline.value: Of 50 local offices, only 22 have adequate income for operational self-financing. Essential headquarters functions not financedbyregistry revenue.

target.value: Operation of key central functions funded by registry revenue; and registry operations streamlined to optimize efficiency andensure adequate and sustainable funding.

actual.value: Center of GIS has been created which is funded by registry revenue.

title.narrative: 1a. Sustainable unit monitors Gosregister performance, provides strategic analysis, and supports improved communication

baseline.value: Project monitoring unit measures and reports on service delivery of every office according to consistent standards. TopGosregister management responds on strategy issues as they arise.

target.value: Permanent unit has capacity and functions effectively with financing from registry operations.

actual.value: Permanent unit has capacity and functions effectively with financing from registry operations.

comment.narrative: Permanent monitoring unit of the GIS center has capacity and functions are financing from registry operations.Achieved.

title.narrative: 2a Novostroiki, lands registered on a systematic basis

baseline.value: Registration of most settlement areas and most private arable land complete. However, coverage gaps in many novostroiki areas aswell as most government buildings and land in urban areas, and in pasture and natural reserve lands.

target.value: Cumulative totals of 10,000 REUs in novostroiki areas registered and subject to progress with the Agricultural Investments andService Project, pasture lands of more than 300 local authorities registered.

actual.value: Registration of REU in novostroiki areas, including sporadic cases has reached 20, 854 including 10, 005 REU systematicallysurveyed in the project. Registration of pasture lands in 395 local authorities is completed.
